			<title>PC Final Fantasy VII re-release</title>
			<link>http://www.graffe.com/forums/showthread.php?73962-Final-Fantasy-VII-re-release&amp;goto=newpost</link>
			<pubDate>Wed, 15 Aug 2012 11:38:26 GMT</pubDate>
			<description><![CDATA[Figured I'd post my first impressions of this re-release (it's not a remake!). 
 
Pro: 
 
- 3D graphics are optionally rendered at high resolutions, making especially battle scenes and the overworld look significantly better than before.* 
- Texture filtering (for 3D graphics) can be toggled. 
-...]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div>Figured I'd post my first impressions of this re-release (it's not a remake!).<br />
<br />
Pro:<br />
<br />
- 3D graphics are <i>optionally</i> rendered at high resolutions, making especially battle scenes and the overworld look significantly better than before.*<br />
- Texture filtering (for 3D graphics) can be toggled.<br />
- Saves are synced with &quot;the cloud&quot;.<br />
- Four language options (English, French, German, Spanish).<br />
- Runs perfectly on new versions of Windows (the original release is a pain in the ass to get working).<br />
- Achivements (for those who care about them).<br />
<br />
<br />
Con:<br />
<br />
- Requires online activation.<br />
- Requires account login (SE or Facebook).<br />
- 2D graphics still low-res. No filtering option for backgrounds.<br />
- Videos badly upscaled (to 1280x896). They still look like crap because Square hasn't bothered to re-render them, but seem to exhibit less compression artifacts than the original PC version.<br />
<br />
<br />
What bothers me the most is Square's ridiculous habit of requiring an internet connection for re-releases of their old games (the Android versions of Final Fantasy I and III suffer from the same). At least the game can supposedly be installed on multiple systems (according to the confirmation email I received, haven't tested it yet).<br />
<br />
<i>* You can achieve a similar look with the PS1 version on an emulator, but the PC version lacks the PS1's &quot;wobble&quot; caused by the lack of a depth buffer.</i></div>

]]></content:encoded>
